<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN HI-TECH FIRMS SEEKING COOPERATION WITH INDIAN COUNTERPARTS
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
New  Delhi,  Jan.  8 (CNA) 01/08/07  17:45:09 (By Kuo Chuan-hsin
and Luis Huang)
</P>
<P>
Viewing India as a strong economic partner, Taiwan's information
technology firms are shifting their investment destinations from
China to India, a mass- circulation Indian newspaper reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to The Financial Express, the combination of Taiwanese
manufacturers' technology hardware manufacturing specialty with
that of Indian software design will help create a win-win
situation for both parties.
</P>
<P>
Hsu Chun-fang, deputy director-general of the Board of Foreign
Trade under Taiwan's Ministry of Economic Affairs was quoted as
saying that Taiwan is targeting India while striving to expand
economic and trade relations with foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Four large-scale delegations made up of government officials and
representatives from relevant industries made fact-finding visits
to India last year to study the feasibility of establishing a
special industrial zone in the country, the newspaper said,
adding that the government-funded Institute for Information
Industry is also planning to set up a research and development
center in India.
</P>
<P>
Moreover,  India' information-related  product  manufacturing
industry, shoe sector and automobile parts and components
industry have also attracted investment from Taiwanese
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
Despite the absence of formal diplomatic relations between Taiwan
and India, the two countries have enjoyed close economic and
trade exchanges, with two-way trade volume amounting to US$2.42
billion in 2005, according to the report.
</P>
